posts.title: Bannon Is Right: The Real Debt Is Over $300 Trillion
posts.content:
Steve Bannon and others who claim the real U.S. debt is much higher than the official national debt (which is currently around $34 trillion) are likely referring to total unfunded liabilities rather than just government-issued debt. When factoring in all financial obligations, hidden spending, and long-term commitments, the true burden on the economy could be well over $300 trillion. Here’s a breakdown of what he might be talking about:

Official National Debt (~$34 Trillion) – This is the publicly acknowledged debt, including Treasury bonds held by the public and government trust funds. Unfunded Liabilities (Estimates Vary, Some Over $200 Trillion) – These are future government obligations that do not have dedicated revenue sources. The biggest contributors are: Social Security: The program will eventually pay out more than it takes in. Medicare: A major driver of long-term debt due to rising healthcare costs. Federal Pensions and Other Entitlements: Long-term obligations to government employees. State and Local Debt – Many states and municipalities also have large pension and healthcare obligations that contribute to overall U.S. debt concerns. Corporate and Consumer Debt – Some analysts consider total U.S. debt across all sectors (government, corporate, and consumer) when discussing “real debt.” If you include these, total U.S. debt exceeds $100 trillion. Derivatives and Financial Liabilities – Some claim that, if you include the notional value of derivatives and global financial obligations tied to the U.S., the total exposure reaches $300 trillion or more. However, derivatives are complex, and not all of their value represents actual debt obligations. Unaccounted Military and Secretive Government Spending – Beyond the official budget, the U.S. government spends untold sums on classified military projects, intelligence operations, and other "black budget" initiatives. Estimates vary, but some reports suggest that trillions of dollars have been spent without full transparency, adding to the hidden financial burden. The Pentagon has failed multiple audits, with entire sums of money going unaccounted for, further complicating the real debt picture. So, when Bannon and others say the "real debt" is $300 trillion, they are likely bundling together government obligations, future entitlement liabilities, corporate and consumer debt, financial derivatives, and hidden military spending.

It’s an alarming figure, but the question is whether all these liabilities will come due at once (which is unlikely). However, the concern remains that as interest rates rise and deficits grow, the government will struggle to keep up with its obligations, leading to economic instability.
